WEBVTT

00:02.658 --> 00:06.063
If you have a Bible, and I hope you do.

00:06.484 --> 00:09.028
Let me invite you to open with me to Acts chapter 27.

00:09.388 --> 00:22.248
And while you're turning there, Acts 27, let me just say, I really, I cannot express in words how good it is to be here right now.

00:22.949 --> 00:31.602
I can't put into words the swell and variety of emotions involved in being here.

00:32.578 --> 00:44.777
Yeah, just can't express how much I miss you and love you as a church and how much my family misses and loves you.

00:44.797 --> 00:51.789
And I was just praying this morning, just thanking God for the abundant grace.

00:51.969 --> 00:57.117
He poured out on my life and my family through you in this room.

00:57.638 --> 01:00.242
So just know we miss you.

01:00.354 --> 01:07.462
Deeply, Miss you, I miss these pastors as I gather together with them this morning just for concentrated time and prayer.

01:08.423 --> 01:10.305
I'm so thankful for those brothers.

01:10.345 --> 01:12.868
I'm so thankful for Matt Mason.

01:13.068 --> 01:16.271
I was thinking about where we'd be in the Word today.

01:16.291 --> 01:17.913
I was remembering back.

01:17.953 --> 01:19.775
This is the last time I preached here.

01:19.995 --> 01:25.121
We were in 2 Timothy 4 and I gave two charges.

01:25.181 --> 01:26.222
I was looking back at the notes.

01:26.563 --> 01:29.746
So charge number one was get a pastor who preaches the Word.

01:29.986 --> 01:33.590
And charge number two is be a people who prioritize the word.

01:34.270 --> 01:39.155
And I praise God for how this has happened, how this is happening.

01:39.215 --> 01:42.138
I'm so thankful for this brother in the way he loves.

01:47.704 --> 01:58.034
And it's just encouraging, so this will sound a little weird, but it's encouraging to be here on the day when you're starting, or you're doing global offering, and then you're gonna vote on budget later, which I did say,

01:58.850 --> 02:05.418
I don't think it was necessarily wise like to add something onto the end of the service when I'm preaching because I'm probably going to go a little long.

02:06.279 --> 02:13.547
So anyway, I don't want to disappoint anybody with like a short sermon today, so I promise not to disappoint you.

02:13.888 --> 02:21.096
So anyway, but even looking at that and looking at the worship guide, so where your treasure is at your heart would be awesome.

02:21.116 --> 02:22.578
So you can tell people's

02:22.658 --> 02:24.000
part by where they're putting the treasure.

02:24.020 --> 02:38.667
And so for me to look at, so is, is Raquel still leading for the spread of the gospel and Birmingham and the nations and the sea of budget where, I think it was $1.7 million, about 20% of the budget devoted to missions and church multiplication locally and globally.

02:38.988 --> 02:46.962
And I trust you know, so maybe you do know, maybe you don't know, that in that much of that money goes to the IMB, where I have the privilege

02:47.106 --> 02:55.619
of leading IMB representing 40,000 plus churches who are working together to say we want to pull together our resources to get the gospel to people who've never heard it.

02:55.899 --> 03:08.178
So even though I'm not able to partner with you in the gospel as pastor anymore, we are in very real ways continuing partnership together for the spread.

03:08.322 --> 03:09.283
of the gospel.

03:09.484 --> 03:12.729
So just a quick update on IMB for anybody who would be interested.

03:12.769 --> 03:13.530
I'll make it really quick.

03:14.311 --> 03:16.474
But we've gone through a challenging couple of years.

03:16.514 --> 03:19.819
So when I got there, came face to face with some financial realities.

03:19.860 --> 03:24.587
We were spending just tens of millions of dollars every year more than we were bringing in.

03:24.607 --> 03:30.416
To the tune of about $210 million over five years, we'd spent more than we had brought in.

03:30.936 --> 03:32.479
And we had different ways of recovering that.

03:32.499 --> 03:37.266
But obviously, that can't keep doing that for very long.

03:37.346 --> 03:46.439
We've made a variety of difficult decisions, but by God's grace, a couple of weeks ago, passed a balanced budget for this next year where our receipts and expenses are matching one another.

03:46.619 --> 03:54.831
And then the best part of that is since 2009, so tons of churches like Raquel send missionaries through the IMB.

03:54.911 --> 03:58.476
So many of the members of this church who are serving overseas are serving through the IMB.

03:58.897 --> 04:05.426
But because of these financial realities, since 2009, the number of those missionaries serving through the IMB has been gradually decreasing.

04:05.634 --> 04:11.283
And so every year since 2009, but this year we're turning that trend around.

04:11.503 --> 04:17.693
And so this next year, Lord willing, it will be more out than before and the budget will match.

04:17.793 --> 04:20.377
So by God's grace, just a journey we've walked through.

04:20.397 --> 04:26.947
I say all that to say, you're a part of this, through your giving now, through your giving to the budget, through your sending, through your going.

04:27.007 --> 04:32.455
I mean, you're a part of what is the largest mission force of its kind in the world.

04:32.936 --> 04:34.098
And I'm just,

04:34.402 --> 04:35.103
I'm thankful.

04:35.323 --> 04:51.805
Like, yeah, I mean, coming back here, it's like, oh, I miss at the same time, like the end, toward which we're working together is every nation tribe telling people gathered around the throne of our king, giving his praise, and we are in a very real way, partnering together, week in and week out toward that end.

04:52.085 --> 04:53.567
So it's good to be back.

04:53.667 --> 04:55.009
We got to dive into the words.

04:55.069 --> 05:02.098
So Matt told me the finishing out series on Acts asked if I could

05:02.306 --> 05:08.975
If I had anything to talk about when it comes to missions, and so I tried to scrounge up some things on that topic.

05:09.115 --> 05:14.603
So I actually want to start by doing something a little different.

05:14.683 --> 05:18.668
I want to spend the first part of our time just telling you a story.

05:18.768 --> 05:24.997
I don't presume to be as good a storyteller as Chris Kinsley, and I don't have props with trees and lights, which would be really cool, but I don't.

05:25.357 --> 05:26.319
It's just me talking.

05:26.819 --> 05:31.666
But I want to start with a story that I hope will make a point that will

05:31.906 --> 05:33.408
lead us right into the words.

05:33.448 --> 05:35.652
So, let's jump into the story.

05:35.672 --> 05:39.899
I want you to imagine with me an eight-year-old boy named Sameer.

05:41.080 --> 05:43.324
Sameer's name means pleasant companion.

05:44.586 --> 05:45.647
Sameer has two sisters.

05:46.228 --> 05:47.210
One is five years old.

05:47.450 --> 05:50.014
Her name is Amira, which means princess.

05:50.655 --> 05:52.638
And it's exactly what she is to Sameer.

05:52.719 --> 05:56.484
Sameer prizes himself on taking care of his princess of a sister.

05:57.145 --> 06:00.050
And he's nothing short of a pleasant companion for her.

06:00.674 --> 06:04.239
And then there's Raja, their baby sister born a short six months ago.

06:04.960 --> 06:05.822
Her name means hope.

06:07.104 --> 06:12.191
So together, they lived in Syria with their father, mother, and grandmother.

06:12.972 --> 06:14.394
Sameer's parents were both teachers.

06:15.075 --> 06:19.181
His dad taught Arabic and the state-run school in Syria while his mom taught music.

06:19.642 --> 06:23.668
They worked hard to provide for their family in a quaint village of about 4,000 people.

06:25.030 --> 06:27.173
Well, it used to be a quaint village.

06:27.954 --> 06:30.418
Their village was situated on the border

06:30.594 --> 06:41.269
of three different provinces in Syria, and over recent years it became trapped in a triangle of terror, Syrian army on one side, the free Syrian army on the other side, and the Russian army in the middle.

06:42.370 --> 06:46.236
Sameer vividly remembers the first time a bomb landed in his village.

06:47.397 --> 06:50.301
He was inside his house playing with the mirror when the door suddenly flew open.

06:50.361 --> 06:55.128
Sameer's dad out of breath from running home as fast as he could began yelling, get out of the house.

06:55.849 --> 06:59.474
A minute later they were huddled together in a makeshift shelter while the sound of

06:59.906 --> 07:01.808
Bombshells shot all around them.

07:02.929 --> 07:09.657
Shrapnel littered the streets and a sure sign of these Syrian villagers that their quaint homes had suddenly become a war zone.

07:11.318 --> 07:14.121
It wasn't long until electricity was out for most of the day.

07:14.782 --> 07:16.244
Schools could no longer function.

07:16.684 --> 07:17.885
Work came to a halt.

07:18.206 --> 07:21.690
Food and water started both becoming scarce.

07:22.671 --> 07:29.458
Bombs would fall day and night, living no semblance of peace at any point for Samir and his family.

07:30.242 --> 07:35.647
Anxiety began to set in for this eight-year-old and his mind, a diversity of side effects.

07:35.667 --> 07:47.198
Samir was turning into a cowering, stuttering version of himself, too scared to sleep at night, just waiting to wake up his sister, sprint with his family to the shelter at any moment.

07:48.399 --> 07:50.401
And one night he overheard his parents talking.

07:51.362 --> 07:53.844
His father said to his mother, we can't stay here anymore.

07:53.884 --> 07:55.286
We need to go somewhere else.

07:56.687 --> 07:59.730
To which Samir's mom asked the obvious question,

08:00.034 --> 08:00.395
Where?

08:00.415 --> 08:05.383
For generations, their families had lived and worked in that village.

08:05.423 --> 08:07.467
Syria is all they'd ever known.

08:07.527 --> 08:08.529
Where would they go?

08:08.569 --> 08:10.613
How would they support themselves?

08:12.055 --> 08:16.843
Sameer's dad shared how he had seen and heard of relocation opportunities.

08:16.864 --> 08:23.455
How if they could just get across Turkey to the Aegean Sea, they could cross over into Greece.

08:23.575 --> 08:25.138
And there, they'd be free.

08:25.346 --> 08:30.211
If only they could get to Greece and they would have passage into the rest of Europe, and then they could start over.

08:31.453 --> 08:33.655
Sameer's mom immediately expressed concern.

08:33.795 --> 08:40.863
She said, do you really think we can travel with your mom and three kids, including a six-month-old baby, hundreds of miles across Syria and then Turkey?

08:41.624 --> 08:44.728
Then how do we get across the Aegean Sea to Europe?

08:44.968 --> 08:45.408
She asked.

08:46.229 --> 08:48.972
And who's to say they won't turn us right around when we get there?

08:48.992 --> 08:51.615
I don't know.

08:51.856 --> 08:54.098
Sameer's dad said as he sunk into silence.

08:55.298 --> 08:57.201
But after a long pause, he spoke again.

08:57.241 --> 08:59.864
I also don't know any other option.

08:59.904 --> 09:04.010
We either stay here and die or we risk our lives and we go.

09:04.050 --> 09:07.755
Within days, the family was packed.

09:08.436 --> 09:10.499
Everybody but the baby had a bag to carry.

09:10.619 --> 09:17.188
And just like that, generations of history and entire family's possessions were reduced to five plastic sacks.

09:17.989 --> 09:21.554
One of which contained all the money Samir's mother and father had saved.

09:22.658 --> 09:27.686
They set out on foot, leaving what used to be the comforts of home behind for a journey into the unknown.

09:28.567 --> 09:35.397
It was about a three-day trip to the Turkish border, some of it by bus, most of it by foot, in light of the various dangers associated with travel on the main roads.

09:36.199 --> 09:38.763
The first night, their family slept in an abandoned coal factory.

09:39.323 --> 09:40.946
The next night was spent in a stable.

09:41.307 --> 09:51.442
The third day posed the greatest challenge, a massive mountain to cross, on foot at the Turkish border, about a nine-hour track with the sounds of bullets and bombs nearby.

09:52.034 --> 09:54.057
They ran out of water about halfway through.

09:54.097 --> 10:02.510
Samir's dad was now carrying Amira, his mom carrying baby Raja, and Samir and his grandmother plotting along behind together.

10:03.311 --> 10:07.677
Every one of them ready to quit if it weren't for the others pushing them along.

10:09.380 --> 10:14.828
But they finally reached Turkey in need of rest and relief, neither of which they would find.

10:16.170 --> 10:18.994
You see, ever since refugees began trekking across

10:19.106 --> 10:21.909
Turkey, an entire industry of exploitation, has begun.

10:22.009 --> 10:23.531
Refugees need simple goods.

10:23.931 --> 10:32.741
Water, food, supplies for the journey to the coast, and a swath of smugglers are there to charge exorbitant prices for everything refugees need.

10:33.782 --> 10:38.667
Samir's dad had no choice but to pay whatever they asked, to get his family whatever they needed.

10:39.208 --> 10:45.234
His money was slipping away slowly, that the highest sum was still left to come.

10:46.018 --> 10:53.225
As they finally approached the coast, they found themselves joined by thousands of other refugees, a sea of humanity seeking asylum.

10:53.725 --> 11:01.693
Samir's dad checked his family into a hostile, humble semblance of a hotel where the family would cram into a small room with one bed.

11:01.973 --> 11:07.859
Samir's grandmother would sleep on it with the baby while the rest of them would sleep side by side on the floor.

11:07.879 --> 11:13.244
As Samir nuzzled up next to his dad that night, he thought about all that he missed.

11:13.304 --> 11:15.506
His home, his friends, his life,

11:16.194 --> 11:19.377
He considered all that he'd seen, the effects of war all around him.

11:20.539 --> 11:22.561
And his tears came to his eyes.

11:23.542 --> 11:26.645
He took solace in the fact that he no longer heard bombs overhead.

11:26.705 --> 11:27.867
At least here they were safe.

11:29.468 --> 11:32.872
The next morning, Samir went with his dad to find a way to cross the sea.

11:33.252 --> 11:36.576
So the system of smugglers at the coast is very active.

11:37.397 --> 11:40.200
And for them it was nearly impossible to tell who you could trust, who you couldn't.

11:40.580 --> 11:45.906
A ferry across the Aegean Sea would cost you or me in this room about $17.

11:46.690 --> 11:56.390
But smugglers are charging refugees approximately $1,000 to $2,000 apiece for each member of a family, including infants to cross to the other side.

11:57.251 --> 11:59.195
And they wouldn't be crossing on a ferry.

11:59.436 --> 12:03.003
They'd be crossing on a small boat or on a rubber dinghy.

12:03.223 --> 12:08.594
It's basically a raft made for about 30 people, with no guarantee that it would make it to the other side.

12:09.474 --> 12:19.908
Samir heard people telling the stories the day before 34 people, including 15 children and four toddlers, had drowned when an overcrowded boat capsized their storms and high winds.

12:20.890 --> 12:28.020
Those 34 joined approximately 2,500 other people who have died trying to get to Greece on those waters.

12:28.060 --> 12:30.724
That great sea has literally become a graveyard.

12:32.546 --> 12:35.410
The journey across the Aegean, you can only imagine, is delicate.

12:35.586 --> 12:46.677
Depending on everything from weather conditions to armed criminals, masked men on jet skis are known to attack boats, smashing into them with sticks, threatening to drown them if they won't surrender whatever valuables they have with them.

12:48.098 --> 12:52.603
After a while, Samir and his dad met a man who said he could get them across for $1,800 apiece.

12:52.623 --> 12:56.006
$1,800 apiece.

12:56.266 --> 12:59.429
That'd be over $10,000 for Samir's family.

13:01.051 --> 13:04.434
Samir's dad knew that would come close to draining his savings.

13:04.546 --> 13:06.028
But what choice did he have?

13:06.088 --> 13:08.551
The living conditions in Turkey were harsh.

13:08.571 --> 13:13.156
There's a reason people are spending their savings and risking their lives to get out of that country.

13:14.758 --> 13:16.620
So Samir's dad reluctantly agreed.

13:17.601 --> 13:20.464
Smuggler said, I'll try to get you on a more sturdy boat, but we will see.

13:20.845 --> 13:23.668
Simply keep your phone by your side and I'll call you when it's time.

13:24.829 --> 13:32.658
Samir and his dad left the meeting with this man, immediately went to buy life jackets, never realized that their quality is so poor that many people have drowned wearing them.

13:33.570 --> 13:37.916
Once they were purchased, Samir and his dad went back to the hostel where the rest of the family was waiting.

13:38.197 --> 13:41.021
They gave them the news, told them they needed to be ready at any time.

13:41.942 --> 13:43.845
That night they received a call from the smuggler.

13:44.626 --> 13:47.230
Too much rain and wind, he said, we can't go tonight.

13:48.111 --> 13:49.614
The next night, the same message would come.

13:50.194 --> 13:54.881
And the next, and the next, until some nights a message never even came.

13:56.003 --> 13:58.066
Samir's dad began to worry if he made a mistake.

13:58.210 --> 14:04.078
working with this particular smuggler, if passage was ever actually going to be a reality as long as they were working with him.

14:04.278 --> 14:13.350
They would pass the days in the hostel, meeting other families, sharing each other's stories, spurring on each other's hope, and what might lie ahead on the other side of the sea.

14:14.232 --> 14:22.683
But that hope was fading fast until one night, the phone rang suddenly, and the voice of the smuggler on the other end said, you can travel on a rubber dinghy tonight.

14:23.043 --> 14:24.626
Come to the meeting place immediately.

14:25.767 --> 14:27.890
And just like that, Samir's dad had a choice.

14:28.514 --> 14:35.986
He'd waited for weeks, hoping his family would be on a boat more sturdy, safe, secure than a small rubber dinghy.

14:36.007 --> 14:38.010
I might miss crashing a jean waves.

14:38.651 --> 14:45.442
Now he had minutes to decide if he was ready to risk his family's life on a rubber dinghy and utter exhaustion from the journey.

14:46.003 --> 14:48.648
Sameer's dad thought, this may be our only chance.

14:49.850 --> 14:54.237
So he turned and he said to his family, grab your bags and life jackets.

14:54.357 --> 14:54.898
Let's go.

14:55.874 --> 15:09.016
Soon, they were crammed into a small van with other refugees making their way through alleys toward a hidden crag in the sea, and there a raft built for 30 people was waiting for 60 refugees arriving in the vans.

15:11.280 --> 15:15.367
They began loading the raft for one by one, cramming closely in next to each other.

15:16.268 --> 15:21.938
As each of them climbed in, they were immediately cold, able to feel the freezing temperature from the water around them.

15:22.722 --> 15:29.675
One of the refugees was appointed by the smugglers to drive the boat, a task that man and nobody else on the boat had ever done.

15:29.735 --> 15:37.048
The smugglers started the engine, pushed them out to shore, and thus began the longest three hours of Samir's short life.

15:38.090 --> 15:40.755
Imagine being crammed into that boat.

15:42.157 --> 15:44.882
See the pitch black darkness.

15:45.698 --> 15:49.963
Feel the shiver of the sea as its waves toss you back and forth.

15:50.063 --> 16:00.995
Hear the sound of people screaming in fear as a man who's never driven a boat before nervously navigates the Aegean sea with 60 lives in his hands.

16:02.336 --> 16:06.701
Sameer looked over at his mom and saw fear on her face for the first time in the journey.

16:08.082 --> 16:15.250
She was clutching his baby sister tightly, knowing that if she or the baby were to fall off now, there's no way the baby would live.

16:16.802 --> 16:29.477
To make matters worse, freezing water was pouring into the boat with every passing wave, which became a major problem as they approached the coast, because the raft was now completely overloaded and it was starting to sag into the sea.

16:30.639 --> 16:33.222
Somebody cried out, water, we need to bail out the water.

16:33.562 --> 16:35.925
And so they began trying to do so with a little avail.

16:35.965 --> 16:36.946
There was too much.

16:38.088 --> 16:40.891
So another person yelled in a panic, wait, we need to shed more weight.

16:41.131 --> 16:44.756
So they began throwing overboard what little valuables they had left among them.

16:45.537 --> 16:46.738
That did little to help.

16:47.202 --> 16:52.508
Something more significant was clearly needed, and it was at this point that Samir's dad suddenly stood up.

16:53.649 --> 17:00.277
He looked into his son's eyes, then across at his wife, and he said, I want you and everybody else in this boat to live.

17:00.417 --> 17:02.680
I'll do my best to meet you on shore.

17:02.960 --> 17:05.503
And without any further hesitation, he jumped.

17:07.185 --> 17:11.570
Samir screamed in horror as his dad, just like that was gone.

17:12.770 --> 17:17.119
His mom, sister, and grandmother were wailing as well, but it was too late.

17:17.179 --> 17:21.928
That loss of weight immediately made a difference, and the raft began moving quickly toward the land.

17:23.010 --> 17:30.084
Everybody relieved, except for Samir and his family, as they now watched his dad disappear into the darkness of the Aegean Sea.

17:32.188 --> 17:33.691
After a time, they arrived on shore.

17:33.711 --> 17:35.154
People started jumping out of the boat.

17:35.234 --> 17:42.383
closed, quickly drenched as they trudged ashore for most of those refugees' shouts of jubilation filled the air.

17:42.443 --> 17:42.984
We've made it.

17:43.004 --> 17:43.985
We've made it to Europe.

17:44.306 --> 17:48.611
They said Samir's family, however, did not join the celebration.

17:49.633 --> 17:55.360
While others ran away from the sea, Samir and his family couldn't take their eyes off of it.

17:55.380 --> 18:03.250
Tears streamed down his mother's face as she now faced the prospect of the journey ahead, of life ahead, apart from her husband.

18:04.930 --> 18:05.511
What do we do?

18:05.631 --> 18:07.834
Mommy, Samir, and Amira asked.

18:09.316 --> 18:10.337
Samir's mom was silent.

18:10.498 --> 18:11.719
She had no idea what to say.

18:13.021 --> 18:18.228
When an aid worker suddenly came running over to them, she had heard the story of what Samir's father had done.

18:18.628 --> 18:22.914
She told them that there were Greek coast guard boats patrolling those waters.

18:23.355 --> 18:26.739
There was a chance, she said, they could find him and pick him up.

18:27.781 --> 18:34.610
So Samir's family now found themselves cleaning this sliver of hope as they came up on shore and wrapped themselves in warm blankets.

18:35.234 --> 18:44.809
And there they waited for an hour, and then two until a Greek Coast Guard ship radioed in and said the man who jumped from the rubber boat has been rescued.

18:46.351 --> 18:50.818
Not long after, they brought him ashore, Samir's family celebration could begin.

18:51.859 --> 18:53.342
But the journey was not over.

18:53.642 --> 18:58.770
A 40-mile walk led them to a processing center where they would wait in line

18:59.042 --> 19:02.467
for papers, for food, for water, for clothing, for everything.

19:02.568 --> 19:05.372
It didn't take long to feel more like cattle than people.

19:06.754 --> 19:09.558
But the refugee camp here was a short-term stay.

19:09.579 --> 19:13.064
Their goal was to get the border of Macedonia as soon as possible.

19:13.384 --> 19:19.474
There they heard was the easiest access en route to Germany, the place where most of these refugees wanted to end up.

19:20.258 --> 19:25.384
So after a night in the camp, Samir's dad wanted them to waste no time and the journey continued.

19:25.404 --> 19:29.929
They caught a bus to a nearby city about 52 miles south of the Macedonian border.

19:30.750 --> 19:38.518
When they arrived there, Samir's dad looked at his wife, kids, and mother realized they did not have the energy for a 52 mile walk.

19:39.339 --> 19:49.170
So we found a taxi driver agreed with that taxi driver to take them to the border for the equivalent of about $300, which was nearly all of the family's remaining money.

19:50.242 --> 19:55.788
Hesitantly, Samir's dad gave the driver the $300 and the family climbed into the taxi.

19:56.849 --> 20:00.753
20 minutes later, though, the driver abruptly stopped and told them to get out of the car.

20:01.915 --> 20:02.896
Samir's dad protested.

20:02.916 --> 20:04.597
I paid you to take us to the border.

20:04.618 --> 20:06.860
He said, I gave you the money you asked us to take to the border.

20:07.100 --> 20:09.263
The taxi driver, though, wouldn't listen.

20:09.523 --> 20:11.485
He said, I'm not taking you any further.

20:11.525 --> 20:13.467
I've taken you as far as you paid me to take you.

20:13.707 --> 20:16.210
